diagnoses.name: Hyperimmunoglobulin E Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare immunodeficiency disorder characterized by high levels of serum IgE, eczema, and recurrent skin and lung infections. Patients can present with dysphagia due to esophageal infections or strictures, and leukocytosis as part of an inflammatory response.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Granulomatous Disease
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that affects the immune system's ability to kill certain bacteria and fungi, leading to increased susceptibility to infections. It can cause granulomas which may affect any system, potentially leading to signs such as dermatitis (including dyshydrotic eczema) and leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Common Variable Immunodeficiency
diagnoses.description: An immunodeficiency disorder characterized by low antibody levels, leading to increased infections. Patients often have autoimmune manifestations that might include skin conditions like eczema and complications causing dysphagia.

diagnoses.name: Severe Combined Immunodeficiency
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder characterized by the profound deficiency of T- and B-lymphocytes, leading to severe recurrent infections. Skin manifestations can include eczema. Leukocytosis may occur in response to infection.

diagnoses.name: Wiskott-Aldrich Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder affecting the immune system and blood clotting. It is characterized by eczema, thrombocytopenia, and an increased risk of infections and leukemia, which can present with leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Graft-versus-host disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when donor bone marrow or stem cells attack the recipient. Symptoms can include skin disorders resembling dyshydrotic eczema, liver dysfunction, and gastrointestinal issues causing dysphagia. Leukocytosis and increased susceptibility to infections can arise due to the immune response.

diagnoses.name: Hypereosinophilic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by the overproduction of eosinophils, a type of white blood cell, leading to inflammation and damage to multiple organs. Skin manifestations can resemble eczema, and dysphagia might occur when the esophagus is involved. Leukocytosis is common.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that mainly affects the salivary and lacrimal glands, leading to dry mouth and eyes. Patients might present with dysphagia due to dryness and have a chronic skin condition resembling eczema. Leukocytosis can happen during systemic flares.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, including the skin, causing rashes that might mimic eczema. Patients can have dysphagia due to esophageal involvement. Increased susceptibility to infections and leukocytosis are common due to both the disease and its treatments.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body. Patients might experience skin symptoms similar to eczema, dysphagia from mucosal involvement, and have an increased risk of infections. Leukocytosis can be a reaction to systemic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Glycemic lability is a common symptom of poorly controlled diabetes.

diagnoses.name: Hyperosmolar Hyperglycemic State
diagnoses.reasoning: This condition may present with glycemic lability and can lead to dehydration, contributing to difficulty focusing vision.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Ketoacidosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause glycemic lability and, due to ketone production, might lead to dehydration, which can cause presyncope and difficulty focusing vision.

diagnoses.name: Sepsis
diagnoses.reasoning: A severe infection like pneumonia can progress to sepsis, which can explain the wide range of symptoms including difficulty focusing vision, presyncope, and migratory edema.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Both hyperthyroidism and hypothyroidism can cause glycemic lability, and hyperthyroidism might cause difficulty focusing vision.

diagnoses.name: Cushing Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: This condition can influence glycemic lability and might contribute to migratory edema and difficulty focusing vision due to changes in cortisol levels.

diagnoses.name: Cardiac Failure
diagnoses.reasoning: Heart failure can cause fluid accumulation, leading to migratory edema and can also precipitate acute events, leading to presyncope.

diagnoses.name: Liver Cirrhosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Liver dysfunction can lead to glycemic lability and cause migratory edema due to low albumin levels.

diagnoses.name: Renal Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Kidney dysfunction can lead to fluid imbalance, causing migratory edema and can impact electrolyte balance, affecting glycemic control.

diagnoses.name: Neurologic Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain conditions like migraines or transient ischemic attacks could explain difficulty focusing vision and presyncope but are less directly related to the other symptoms.

diagnoses.rationale: Connective tissue disorder that can affect skin, joints, and blood vessel walls. May present with joint hypermobility which could contribute to fibrosis over time, and in some cases, may lead to complications such as interstitial cystitis. Oral pain can be associated with dental issues common in Ehlers-Danlos. Obsessive-compulsive behavior and delayed puberty are less directly related but can occur in the context of broader systemic involvement or as secondary features.

While primarily affecting the kidneys, cyst development can lead to fibrosis. Interstitial cystitis might be observed as a secondary condition due to urinary tract involvement. Though oral pain and delayed puberty are less commonly associated, the extensive nature of this disease can affect overall health, potentially impacting developmental timelines and causing stress-related behaviors including obsessive-compulsive behavior.

An autoimmune condition that can affect the skin, joints, kidneys, brain, and other organs. It can cause widespread inflammation and fibrosis in various organs. Interstitial cystitis could be part of its manifestation in the urinary system. Oral pain can result from lupus-related lesions. Lupus can also have neurological and psychological manifestations, possibly explaining obsessive-compulsive behavior. Delayed puberty may occur in the context of systemic illness or chronic inflammation.

An autoimmune disease affecting the body's moisture-producing glands. Primary symptoms include dryness in the mouth (which can lead to oral pain) and eyes, but it can also cause systemic issues such as joint pain and fibrosis. Interstitial cystitis can be associated with Sjögren's as part of its systemic involvement. Psychological symptoms and delayed puberty are less directly associated but can occur as indirect effects of chronic illness.

A chromosomal disorder affecting females, where one of the X chromosomes is missing or partially missing. It can lead to delayed puberty due to ovarian failure. Turner syndrome could indirectly relate to fibrosis, especially of the ovaries, though connections to interstitial cystitis and obsessive-compulsive behavior are less direct. Oral pain could be related to structural and dental anomalies common in Turner syndrome.

A genetic disorder that affects the body's connective tissue, potentially leading to fibrosis in various organs and systems. While mainly characterized by long limbs and fingers, cardiovascular abnormalities, and lens dislocation, it can have systemic effects that might indirectly relate to interstitial cystitis, oral pain, and delayed puberty. Obsessive-compulsive behavior is not a common manifestation but could be present due to psychological factors or as a co-morbidity.

A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. While not directly causing fibrosis, it is associated with painful conditions like interstitial cystitis. Oral pain can be present due to associated conditions such as temporomandibular joint disorder. Obsessive-compulsive behavior might be more indicative of the psychological impact of chronic pain. Fibromyalgia does not typically affect puberty timing.

A birth defect in which nerves are missing from parts of the intestine, leading to issues with passing stool. It is primarily known for causing intestinal problems but can be associated with broader developmental delays, possibly influencing puberty timing. While less directly related to interstitial cystitis, fibrosis can occur in the affected regions of the intestine. Oral pain and obsessive-compulsive behavior are not typically associated but can exist as comorbidities or secondary complications.

A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. It can cause a wide range of symptoms, from physical disabilities to psychological problems, including obsessive-compulsive behavior. While not directly causing fibrosis, MS can lead to bladder issues that may mimic or exacerbate symptoms of interstitial cystitis. Oral pain can occur due to lesions in the brain that affect nerve control. Delayed puberty is less commonly associated.

A complication of some kinds of bone marrow transplants, where donated bone marrow or peripheral blood stem cells view the recipient's body as foreign and attack it. It can lead to fibrosis in various organs along with oral pain due to mucosal involvement. While interstitial cystitis specifically is less commonly reported, urinary complications can occur. Obsessive-compulsive behaviors and delayed puberty are not direct symptoms but can arise in the context of systemic illness and chronic health issues.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that is often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light. Aura symptoms can include visual disturbances such as scintillating scotomas.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death. Symptoms can include headache, weakness on one side of the body, and ataxia.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Symptoms can include headaches, nausea or vomiting, and weakness or loss of balance.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). Symptoms can include fatigue, difficulty walking (ataxia), and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. In most cases, Meniere's disease affects only one ear. Symptoms can include vomiting and headache.

diagnoses.name: Viral Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the brain caused by a virus. Symptoms can include headache, fever, confusion, drowsiness, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Intoxication
diagnoses.description: Exposure to a toxic substance that affects the brain. Symptoms can vary widely but can include vomiting, headache, and ataxia.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from a blockage or damage in the vertebral arteries or the basilar artery. Symptoms can include difficulty walking (ataxia), weakness, and visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Hemorrhagic Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when a blood vessel in your brain leaks or ruptures. Symptoms include sudden headache, vomiting, weakness, and decreased coordination (ataxia).

diagnoses.name: Migrainous Infarction
diagnoses.description: A rare form of ischemic stroke that occurs during a migraine with aura. Symptoms include migraine symptoms like visual scintillation, followed by a stroke-like weakness and possibly altered coordination.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms but is frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Tension-type headache
diagnoses.details: The most common type of headache, often described as feeling like a tight band around the head. Symptoms may include dull, aching head pain; sensation of tightness or pressure across the forehead or on the sides and back of the head; tenderness on scalp, neck, and shoulder muscles.

diagnoses.name: Cluster headache
diagnoses.details: A condition that produces severe, sudden headache pain, typically around one eye or one side of the head, along with symptoms like redness or tearing of the eye, runny or stuffy nose, and swelling or sweating of the face.

diagnoses.name: Medication overuse headache
diagnoses.details: Headaches arising from or becoming progressively worse after the overuse of headache pain medications. Symptoms might mimic those of the underlying primary headache the medications were initially taken for.

diagnoses.name: Viral meningitis
diagnoses.details: An infection of the meninges, the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord. Common symptoms include headache, fever, stiffness of the neck, sensitivity to light, sleepiness, or trouble waking up.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid hemorrhage
diagnoses.details: Bleeding in the space between the brain and the tissue covering the brain, presenting with a sudden, severe headache, often described as the 'worst headache' ever experienced. It may be accompanied by nausea, vomiting, stiff neck, blurred vision, and consciousness changes.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.details: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain or central spine canal. Symptoms depend on the tumor size, type, and location but often include headaches (usually worse in the morning), nausea, vomiting, lack of balance, speech problems, and sensory changes.

diagnoses.name: Temporal arteritis
diagnoses.details: An inflammation of blood vessels, typically in the head, causing headache, scalp tenderness, jaw pain, vision problems, and sometimes life-threatening complications if left untreated.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic intracranial hypertension
diagnoses.details: A condition characterized by increased pressure inside the skull without a detectable cause. Symptoms include headache, vision problems, ringing in the ears, and neck stiffness.

diagnoses.name: Carbon monoxide poisoning
diagnoses.details: Exposure to carbon monoxide gas can lead to headaches, weakness, dizziness, nausea, shortness of breath, confusion, blurred vision, and loss of consciousness.
